(61854, -1, 'options_options_vbblog_url_text', 'cphelptext', '<p><b>\r\nThis feature requires that the "Always use Forum URL as Base Path" be set to yes.\r\n</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nThis will override the main Forum URL setting for blog pages to allow the blog pages to be accessed from a different directory than the rest of vBulletin.  This value can either be an absolute URL in which case it fully overrides the Forum URL or it can be a relative URL, in which case it is appended to Forum URL.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nFor example, if vBulletin is located at http://example.com/vbulletin then entering a value of "blog" will result in the blog being located at  http://example.com/vbulletin/blog. A value of "http://www.example.com/blog" will result in the blog being located at http://www.example.com/blog.  All vBulletin URLs must have the same host name.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nIn addition to setting the Blog Component URL, you will need to take the following steps in order for the blog to work in the new location.\r\n</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>If you are locating the blog in a directory other than a direct subdirectory of the vBulletin directory (http://example.com/vbulletin/blog in the above example), then edit blog/vb_dir.php in the do_not_upload directory of your download package to set the vBulletin install directory.  Instructions are given in that file.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>Upload the blog files directory from the do_not_upload directory to the directory you want the blog to be located in. If you want the blog to be in http://example.com/vbulletin/myblog, create a subdirectory in your vBulletin directory called myblog and upload the blog files there.</li>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\nIf you are using rewrite friendly URLs, you will need to copy the .htaccess file from do_not_upload/rewrite/apache2/blog to the stub directory before uploading.\r\n</li>\r\n\r\n<li>\r\nIf you are using a different domain, such as blog.example.com versus www.example.com then you will need a crossdomain.xml file for the asset manager flash upload. Create a file called "crossdomain.xml" and place it in your blog subdirectory with the following contents modified to suit your domain.\r\n<div style="border:1px dashed red; margin:4px; padding:4px; white-space:pre">&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;UTF-8&quot;?&gt;\r\n&lt;cross-domain-policy xmlns:xsi=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance&quot; xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation=&quot;http://www.adobe.com/xml/schemas/PolicyFile.xsd&quot;&gt;\r\n  &lt;allow-access-from domain=&quot;*.example.com&quot;/&gt;\r\n	&lt;site-control permitted-cross-domain-policies=&quot;master-only&quot;/&gt;\r\n  &lt;allow-http-request-headers-from domain=&quot;*.example.com&quot; headers=&quot;*&quot; secure=&quot;true&quot;/&gt;\r\n&lt;/cross-domain-policy&gt;</div>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><b>\r\nIf the cookie path option is set for the site, it needs to be general enough to include all vBulletin URLs. For example, if vBulletin is located at www.host.com/mysite/vbulletin but the then is located at www.mysite.com/mysite/blog then a cookie path of "mysite" will work, but a cookie path of "mysite/vbulletin" will not work because the cookies will not be sent to pages in the mysite/then directory.\r\n</b></p>', 'vbblog', 'freddie', 1318892691, '4.1.8 Beta 1', 0),
(61840, -1, 'options_options_vbblog_tagcloud_searchhistory_text', 'cphelptext', 'The number of days that tag searching information should be stored for. This information is used to build the tag cloud.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n0 will keep data around permanently.', 'vbblog', 'freddie', 1231202605, '2.0.1', 0),
